onergan's eleven years of study of the thought of Thomas Aquinas. The work is considered by many to be a breakthrough in the history of Lonergan's theology and a foundation upon which his later contributions were constructed. Here he interprets aspects in the writing of Aquinas relevant to trinitarian theory and, as in most of Lonergan's work, one of the principal aims is to assist the reader in the search to understand the workings of the human mind.Verbum: Word and Idea in Aquinas is a vital component of Lonergan's oeuvre, and of continuing relevance to trinitarian theology, Aquinas studies, and inquiries into human cognition.Bernard Lonergan (1904-1984), a professor of theology, taught at Regis College, Harvard University, and Boston College. An established author known for his Insight and Method in Theology, Lonergan received numerous honorary doctorates, was a Companion of the Order of Canada in 1971 and was named as an original members of the International Theological Commission by Pope Paul VI.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aCrowe, Frederick E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowe, S.J., Frederick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDool, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoran, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoran, S.J., Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268303740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442683037423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442683037.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of